--- !u!114 &2023515562
MonoBehaviour:
  m_ObjectHideFlags: 0
  m_CorrespondingSourceObject: {fileID: 0}
  m_PrefabInstance: {fileID: 0}
  m_PrefabAsset: {fileID: 0}
  m_GameObject: {fileID: 2023515561}
  m_Enabled: 1
  m_EditorHideFlags: 0
  m_Script: {fileID: 11500000, guid: f86626367efa8114bbc16290644a386f, type: 3}
  m_Name: 
  m_EditorClassIdentifier: '::'
  ui: {fileID: 868776318}
  fpsController: {fileID: 169532084}
  excavationUI: {fileID: 548421995}
  input: {fileID: 808567766}
  AIText: {fileID: 1786518115}
  serverBaseUrl: https://digital-ty59.onrender.com
  data: "In the Lambayeque region, at well-known sites like Sipan and \xDAcupe, copper
    and copper alloy artifacts (especially tumbaga) make up a large portion of the
    materials recovered from the elite tombs of the northern Mochica. Unlike the
    typical view of the Gallinazo based on evidence from the southern north coast
    region, the Northern Gallinazo that occupied the Lambayeque appear to have been
    not only a politically important regional polity, but also a metallurgically
    important entity whose relationship with the Mochica were inextricably tied to
    copper ore. What is the Northern Gallinazo? In the last 30 years, perspectives
    on the Gallinazo and the Vir\xFA have changed significantly, but there is still
    a lack of understanding of the Northern Gallinazo that lived in the Lambayeque
    region. The archaeological definition I have put forth recently defines the Northern
    Gallinazo based on four fundamental criteria that apply to their sites in the
    Lambayeque region during the first millennium. These settlement pattern criteria
    include:\r\n\r\n(1) iconic corporate (monumental) architecture,\r\n\r\n(2) mortuary
    practices that include the presence of well-defined cemeteries,\r\n\r\n(3) a
    distinctive art style that expresses shared beliefs, and\r\n\r\n(4) an association
    with copper in terms of mining and smelting in particular\r\nThese characteristics
    define the major sites of Huaca Letrada and Songoy-Cojal, situated in the valleys
    of La Leche and Za\xF1a, respectively, potentially at other yet-to-be-studied
    sites as well."
  toggleKey: 9
